{
  "texts": [
    "In facial recognition, the diversity and representation of training datasets are critical to avoid algorithmic biases and ensure equitable recognition across various demographics (Kuhlman et al. 2020; Lee et al. 2019).",
    "At its core, facial recognition involves manually curating datasets encompassing various ethnicities, ages, and facial expressions to train robust and unbiased algorithms (Coe and Atay 2021).",
    "Similarly, in paleontology, preprocessing techniques must be designed to maintain the fidelity of fossil data across different specimens.",
    "For instance, merging images from different modalities, such as SEM and OM, necessitates normalization and calibration to accommodate the distinct features.",
    "This fusion could involve adjusting for scale discrepancies, aligning images for accurate overlay, and applying a color correction to ensure that the composite images accurately represent the original fossils without favoring a particular modality."
  ]
}